Other questions?

00:34:13.280 --> 00:34:18.445
Okay, let me show you some
things in--work in progress,

00:34:18.445 --> 00:34:23.611
and in particular space
missions that are being planned

00:34:23.611 --> 00:34:28.931
to explore this further.
So, the first of these is the

00:34:28.931 --> 00:34:33.576
so-called Kepler Mission,
which is going to look for

00:34:33.576 --> 00:34:36.798
transits.
I showed you the Hubble Space

00:34:36.798 --> 00:34:39.660
Telescope, transit curve,
which is much,

00:34:39.660 --> 00:34:43.769
much better than anything you
can do from the ground.

00:34:43.769 --> 00:34:46.699
So, obviously the place to look
for transits is in space.

00:34:46.699 --> 00:34:49.903
From space you could see
transits the size of Earths--of

00:34:49.903 --> 00:34:52.815
planets the size of Earth,
whereas from the ground,

00:34:52.815 --> 00:34:54.969
you wouldn't be able to see
that.

00:34:54.969 --> 00:34:58.407
And also--and so what they want
to do is send up a mission

00:34:58.407 --> 00:35:02.146
that's going to do nothing but
make high precision measurements

00:35:02.146 --> 00:35:04.739
of stars in order to look for
transits.

00:35:04.739 --> 00:35:07.504
So, the problem with the space
telescope is everybody wants to

00:35:07.504 --> 00:35:09.805
use it for all kinds of things.
There's relatively

00:35:09.805 --> 00:35:12.670
little--limited amounts of time
for any one particular project.

00:35:12.670 --> 00:35:16.123
It's also not perfectly
designed for making these kinds

00:35:16.123 --> 00:35:19.361
of transits observations,
so this is going to be a

00:35:19.361 --> 00:35:23.202
mission which is set up for the
express purpose of making very

00:35:23.202 --> 00:35:27.170
high precision measurements of
the brightness of stars over,

00:35:27.170 --> 00:35:30.989
and over, and over again.
And the problem with this is

00:35:30.989 --> 00:35:35.401
just the general problem with
transits: that you only see the

00:35:35.401 --> 00:35:38.409
ones that are edge-on.
So, you've got to look at lots

00:35:38.409 --> 00:35:40.718
and lots of stars.
Even if lots of them have

00:35:40.718 --> 00:35:43.289
planets, you'll only see a few
transits.

00:35:43.289 --> 00:35:45.627
But this is designed to carry
out that mission,

00:35:45.627 --> 00:35:48.219
so they're going to be lots of
transits observed,

00:35:48.219 --> 00:35:51.738
including transits from
Earth-like--from Earth-sized

00:35:51.738 --> 00:35:53.726
stars.
So, this will be the first

00:35:53.726 --> 00:35:56.929
moment when this thing gets
launched that we'll really have

00:35:56.929 --> 00:36:00.409
a good handle on being able to
detect an Earth-sized planet.

00:36:00.409 --> 00:36:03.625
So, if the aliens have launched
their equivalent of Kepler,

00:36:03.625 --> 00:36:05.510
they're looking at us right
now,

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:09.016
provided our Solar System
happens to be exactly edge-on

00:36:09.016 --> 00:36:12.651
from their perspective.
This is due to launch in a year

00:36:12.651 --> 00:36:14.539
or two.
It's under construction.

00:36:14.539 --> 00:36:17.674
It's ready to roll,
and this thing will be up in

00:36:17.674 --> 00:36:21.343
space taking data by the
time--within the next couple of

00:36:21.343 --> 00:36:24.096
years.
So, that's an exciting thing to

00:36:24.096 --> 00:36:27.081
look forward to.
A little bit further into the

00:36:27.081 --> 00:36:30.128
future is something called SIM,
this is the Space

00:36:30.128 --> 00:36:33.429
Interferometry Mission,
and this does astrometry.

00:36:33.429 --> 00:36:37.659
And it's going to improve the
accuracy of positions of stars

00:36:37.659 --> 00:36:41.190
from what we now have,
which is in the milli-arc

00:36:41.190 --> 00:36:43.870
second range,
1/1000 of an arc second,

00:36:43.870 --> 00:36:49.389
to the micro-arc second range,
1/1,000,000 of an arc second.

00:36:49.389 --> 00:36:54.533
And again, as we just did in
that little calculation,

00:36:54.533 --> 00:36:58.984
that will, in principle,
enable us to look for

00:36:58.984 --> 00:37:03.115
Earth-like systems.
Now, the limitation on this is

00:37:03.115 --> 00:37:06.951
that--is this business that for
astrometry, you have to look at

00:37:06.951 --> 00:37:09.240
nearby stars,
and the nearer the star,

00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:12.428
the better.
And if you get far out into

00:37:12.428 --> 00:37:16.581
these--into the galaxy,
then the method becomes less

00:37:16.581 --> 00:37:19.193
sensitive.
It's also true that,

00:37:19.193 --> 00:37:23.774
you know, this method favors
long orbits, and space missions

00:37:23.774 --> 00:37:26.570
tend not to last for forty
years.

00:37:26.570 --> 00:37:29.884
And so, if you're looking for
Neptune, which has,

00:37:29.884 --> 00:37:32.440
you know, a many-decade-long
orbit,

00:37:32.440 --> 00:37:34.894
it's not clear that this is
going to be around for long

00:37:34.894 --> 00:37:36.940
enough to actually make those
measurements.

00:37:36.940 --> 00:37:40.335
So, this astrometry thing is
kind of squeezed between the

00:37:40.335 --> 00:37:43.487
requirement of the method to
have long orbits and the

00:37:43.487 --> 00:37:46.943
requirement of human beings to
get results in a relatively

00:37:46.943 --> 00:37:49.439
short amount of time.
Nevertheless,

00:37:49.439 --> 00:37:53.142
this will be a factor of a
thousand improvement over what

00:37:53.142 --> 00:37:56.670
we can do from the ground.
This mission is authorized.

00:37:56.670 --> 00:37:58.109
It's kind of under
construction,

00:37:58.109 --> 00:38:00.755
but it's one of those things
where it's going to launch in

00:38:00.755 --> 00:38:03.798
five to seven years.
That was also true five to

00:38:03.798 --> 00:38:06.716
seven years ago.
And it will probably--on our

00:38:06.716 --> 00:38:10.265
pessimistic days we think it
will still be true five to seven

00:38:10.265 --> 00:38:12.894
years from now.
It's always five years in the

00:38:12.894 --> 00:38:15.807
future, both for technical
reasons, and for funding and

00:38:15.807 --> 00:38:18.821
political reasons.
But there's some feeling that

00:38:18.821 --> 00:38:22.650
one of these days they'll
actually get around to doing it.

00:38:22.650 --> 00:38:25.893
But it's certainly further in
the future than the Kepler

00:38:25.893 --> 00:38:28.736
Mission is.
And then, the great granddaddy

00:38:28.736 --> 00:38:32.680
of all planet missions is
something called the Terrestrial

00:38:32.680 --> 00:38:34.480
Planet Finder,
the TPF.

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:39.828
This is a huge NASA commitment,
and they want to directly image

00:38:39.828 --> 00:38:42.107
the planet.
So, this is fundamentally

00:38:42.107 --> 00:38:44.928
different from everything else.
This is--we're going to

00:38:44.928 --> 00:38:48.070
actually take a picture of the
light from the planet.

00:38:48.070 --> 00:38:50.642
We're going to give up this
silly business of observing the

00:38:50.642 --> 00:38:52.550
star to infer the presence of
the planet.

00:38:52.550 --> 00:38:54.980
We're actually going to look at
the planet itself.

00:38:54.980 --> 00:38:57.510
In order to do that,
you have to get rid of the

00:38:57.510 --> 00:39:00.257
light from the star.
You have to blank out the light

00:39:00.257 --> 00:39:03.283
of the star, because otherwise,
as we saw, it'll drown out the

00:39:03.283 --> 00:39:04.966
planet.
And there are a couple of

00:39:04.966 --> 00:39:09.329
different ways you can do it.
One is basically just masking.

00:39:09.329 --> 00:39:13.779
You just put a big opaque thing
somewhere in the optical path of

00:39:13.779 --> 00:39:16.524
the telescope,
and it just blocks out the

00:39:16.524 --> 00:39:19.317
light of the star,
but it's carefully sized so

00:39:19.317 --> 00:39:22.670
that the light of stuff around
it can still get in.

00:39:22.670 --> 00:39:25.335
There are also more
sophisticated optical

00:39:25.335 --> 00:39:28.199
methods--something called
interferometry,

00:39:28.199 --> 00:39:31.163
which I won't explain right
now, which can have the same

00:39:31.163 --> 00:39:33.750
effect of nulling out the light
from the star.

00:39:33.750 --> 00:39:36.920
And so, we then observe the
planetary light directly.

00:39:36.920 --> 00:39:39.942
The best way to do this is not
in optical light but in

00:39:39.942 --> 00:39:42.776
infrared.
Optical light is where stars

00:39:42.776 --> 00:39:46.911
give out most of their light.
Planets give out most of their

00:39:46.911 --> 00:39:49.259
light in the infrared.
You may be aware,

00:39:49.259 --> 00:39:52.401
we all glow in the dark,
but we glow in the dark in the

00:39:52.401 --> 00:39:54.593
infrared,
that's why the military uses

00:39:54.593 --> 00:39:57.579
those interesting infrared
goggles, which turn everything

00:39:57.579 --> 00:40:00.568
green.
What those do is they take

00:40:00.568 --> 00:40:05.489
infrared photons and they ingest
infrared photons.

00:40:05.489 --> 00:40:08.847
And they emit green light so
that you can see infrared,

00:40:08.847 --> 00:40:12.079
and that's how they do these
night vision goggles.

00:40:12.079 --> 00:40:15.230
And that's because at the
temperatures on ordinary

00:40:15.230 --> 00:40:17.480
planets, we glow in the
infrared,

00:40:17.480 --> 00:40:20.969
which is why you don't see each
other glowing in the dark,

00:40:20.969 --> 00:40:23.539
because your eyes don't detect
infrared.

00:40:23.539 --> 00:40:25.582
But if you're going to be
looking for planets,

00:40:25.582 --> 00:40:28.396
you're much better off looking
in the infrared than in ordinary

00:40:28.396 --> 00:40:30.252
light.
And then, once you can see the

00:40:30.252 --> 00:40:32.449
light from a planet,
you get to do a really cool

00:40:32.449 --> 00:40:34.807
thing,
which is, you get to examine

00:40:34.807 --> 00:40:39.028
the spectrum of that planet to
find out what the atmosphere is

00:40:39.028 --> 00:40:41.687
made of.
And we talked a little bit

00:40:41.687 --> 00:40:45.702
about spectral features,
which come from different atoms

00:40:45.702 --> 00:40:48.503
or molecules.
And once you actually see the

00:40:48.503 --> 00:40:51.940
light from the planet as opposed
to the light from the star,

00:40:51.940 --> 00:40:54.915
you can actually study in
detail what that star's--what

00:40:54.915 --> 00:40:57.010
that planet's atmosphere is made
of.

00:40:57.010 --> 00:41:00.430
This, by the way,
is how one goes about detecting

00:41:00.430 --> 00:41:02.986
life on planet Earth.
There was a very cute

00:41:02.986 --> 00:41:05.885
experiment a little while ago.
They were sending a mission to

00:41:05.885 --> 00:41:08.873
Jupiter, the Galileo Mission,
which is now at Jupiter doing

00:41:08.873 --> 00:41:11.107
science.
But the way they did it was

00:41:11.107 --> 00:41:13.571
funny.
They sent it not outward toward

00:41:13.571 --> 00:41:15.800
Jupiter, but inward toward
Venus.

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:17.755
It took a swing around Venus.
It turns out,

00:41:17.755 --> 00:41:20.300
if you do it right,
and you swing around a planet,

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:23.405
you can pick up extra speed.
And so, to get this thing out

00:41:23.405 --> 00:41:25.571
to Jupiter, they had it swing
around Venus,

00:41:25.571 --> 00:41:28.150
then come back to Earth and
swing around Earth.

00:41:28.150 --> 00:41:30.054
And each time it did one of
these swings,

00:41:30.054 --> 00:41:32.340
it picked up speed,
so it got to Jupiter actually

00:41:32.340 --> 00:41:35.150
faster that way--a very clever
bit of orbital dynamics.

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:37.983
But the consequence of it was
that this mission,

00:41:37.983 --> 00:41:41.479
one of our prime missions to
look at other planets with all

00:41:41.479 --> 00:41:45.096
the various instruments that we
like to look at other planets

00:41:45.096 --> 00:41:47.710
with,
swung by near to Earth.

00:41:47.710 --> 00:41:50.940
And so, somebody had the very
clever idea, let's use our

00:41:50.940 --> 00:41:54.346
standard suite of exploration
instruments and see if we can

00:41:54.346 --> 00:41:57.458
detect the existence of life on
Earth using one of the

00:41:57.458 --> 00:42:00.689
satellites that we used to
explore the rest of the Solar

00:42:00.689 --> 00:42:02.656
System.
And people had all kinds of

00:42:02.656 --> 00:42:04.710
thoughts about what would be
detectable--you know,

00:42:04.710 --> 00:42:06.894
cities at night,
you know, you would be able to

00:42:06.894 --> 00:42:10.004
see lights on the dark side,
the Great Wall of China,

00:42:10.004 --> 00:42:12.320
you would be able to
detect--no.

00:42:12.320 --> 00:42:16.867
Turns out that the strongest
sign of life on Earth is the

00:42:16.867 --> 00:42:20.440
fact that the atmosphere
contains methane.

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:23.940
Now, the atmosphere,
of course, has a lot of oxygen.

00:42:23.940 --> 00:42:26.886
Methane, you may recall,
is CH4, and if you put a little

00:42:26.886 --> 00:42:29.779
bit of methane into an oxygen
atmosphere it immediately

00:42:29.779 --> 00:42:32.887
dissociates and you get water
and carbon dioxide because of

00:42:32.887 --> 00:42:35.640
all the free oxygen.
So there shouldn't be any

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:37.761
methane in the atmosphere,
but there is,

00:42:37.761 --> 00:42:40.808
and you can detect it by
looking at the infrared spectrum

00:42:40.808 --> 00:42:43.187
of the atmosphere.
Now, what does it mean that

00:42:43.187 --> 00:42:44.650
there's methane in our
atmosphere?

00:42:44.650 --> 00:42:48.315
It means there's a continuous
source of methane pumping into

00:42:48.315 --> 00:42:51.680
the atmosphere all the time.
What is the source of that

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:54.114
methane?
It is, as Carl Sagan,

00:42:54.114 --> 00:42:57.580
delicately put it,
bovine flatulence.

00:42:57.580 --> 00:43:00.496
Cow farts.
And just digestion,

00:43:00.496 --> 00:43:04.626
in general, has an output of
methane, which is continually

00:43:04.626 --> 00:43:08.237
piping into the atmosphere.
And if that weren't happening,

00:43:08.237 --> 00:43:10.967
that happens from biological
activity, and if that weren't

00:43:10.967 --> 00:43:12.976
happening,
there wouldn't be any methane

00:43:12.976 --> 00:43:15.401
observable in the atmosphere.
So, what you do is,

00:43:15.401 --> 00:43:18.531
if you find some other planet,
if you look at the atmospheric

00:43:18.531 --> 00:43:20.677
chemistry,
and you see if there's

00:43:20.677 --> 00:43:24.814
something in there that's out of
equilibrium that could only be

00:43:24.814 --> 00:43:28.150
continually replenished by
biological activity.

00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:32.355
And having both oxygen and
methane at the same time is one

00:43:32.355 --> 00:43:35.048
such indicator.
So, the hope would be that we

00:43:35.048 --> 00:43:37.230
could not only see the light
from the planet,

00:43:37.230 --> 00:43:40.255
but we'd be able to detect the
presence of biological activity

00:43:40.255 --> 00:43:42.225
as well.
So how do you go about doing

00:43:42.225 --> 00:43:45.289
this?
Bovine flatulence equals

00:43:45.289 --> 00:43:51.196
life--words to live by.
Let's see, so here's how you do

00:43:51.196 --> 00:43:52.728
it.
You need to have very high

00:43:52.728 --> 00:43:54.687
resolution;
you need to be able to separate

00:43:54.687 --> 00:43:57.237
the light from the star,
from the light from the planet,

00:43:57.237 --> 00:43:58.860
to the greatest extent
possible.

00:43:58.860 --> 00:44:02.733
Turns out, the way you do this
is you have space telescopes

00:44:02.733 --> 00:44:06.451
spaced pretty widely apart.
That gives you the best handle

00:44:06.451 --> 00:44:09.255
on the resolution.
But they have to know where

00:44:09.255 --> 00:44:12.918
each other is to a precision
very substantially greater than

00:44:12.918 --> 00:44:16.269
the wavelength of the light that
they're observing.

00:44:16.269 --> 00:44:20.084
And so, they need to be able to
tell the distance apart of these

00:44:20.084 --> 00:44:23.717
things to tiny fractions of a
meter--"picometer metrology" is

00:44:23.717 --> 00:44:27.252
the technical word.
A picometer is 10^(-12) meters

00:44:27.252 --> 00:44:31.179
and metrology is just measuring
how far apart you are.

00:44:31.179 --> 00:44:34.642
So, they need to be able to
figure out--to formation fly,

00:44:34.642 --> 00:44:38.537
and know how far apart they are
to about the width of an atom or

00:44:38.537 --> 00:44:40.332
so.
You want to image in the

00:44:40.332 --> 00:44:43.216
infrared.
Mid-infrared imaging wants you

00:44:43.216 --> 00:44:47.122
to--pushes you beyond Jupiter.
The problem is that inside the

00:44:47.122 --> 00:44:49.441
orbit of Jupiter,
there's all this warm dust in

00:44:49.441 --> 00:44:51.844
our Solar System.
And so, it's like the sky is

00:44:51.844 --> 00:44:54.333
bright all the time from all the
infrared emission,

00:44:54.333 --> 00:44:57.012
from the dust.
So, you've got to go out into

00:44:57.012 --> 00:45:00.110
the colder parts of the Solar
System to do this.

00:45:00.110 --> 00:45:02.577
So we're--what we're going to
do, the plan is,

00:45:02.577 --> 00:45:05.320
you're going to build a half
dozen or so things,

00:45:05.320 --> 00:45:08.353
each of which is about ten
times the size of the space

00:45:08.353 --> 00:45:10.835
telescope.
We're going to move them out

00:45:10.835 --> 00:45:14.875
beyond Jupiter and formation fly
them in this--to this extremely

00:45:14.875 --> 00:45:17.537
high precision.
This is not something we're

00:45:17.537 --> 00:45:20.544
capable of doing right now.
But there is a twenty-five

00:45:20.544 --> 00:45:22.831
year-old;
twenty-five year so-called

00:45:22.831 --> 00:45:25.695
roadmap, a series of missions
along the way,

00:45:25.695 --> 00:45:28.891
which is going to
simultaneously be good missions

00:45:28.891 --> 00:45:32.030
in their own right,
and develop the technology.

00:45:32.030 --> 00:45:36.383
SIM is one of these missions.
It's going to develop the high

00:45:36.383 --> 00:45:39.539
precision spatial imaging that
you need for this.

00:45:39.539 --> 00:45:43.986
JWST is the acronym for the
next-generation space telescope,

00:45:43.986 --> 00:45:46.849
which is due to be launched in
2012.

00:45:46.849 --> 00:45:50.724
That's basically one such
telescope, but orbiting the

00:45:50.724 --> 00:45:52.420
Earth.
That's a milestone.

00:45:52.420 --> 00:45:55.230
And there are various other
milestones along this roadmap.

00:45:55.230 --> 00:45:57.942
And the hope is that in
twenty-five years,

00:45:57.942 --> 00:46:00.588
with, you know,
25 to 50 billion dollars,

00:46:00.588 --> 00:46:02.969
we could actually do this
thing.

00:46:02.969 --> 00:46:06.684
And so, here's the little
artist's conception of these

00:46:06.684 --> 00:46:10.820
guys flying in formation outside
of the orbit of Jupiter.

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:13.207
Then, I guess this represents
the Sun down in the middle of

00:46:13.207 --> 00:46:15.647
the Solar System.
They're looking out this way,

00:46:15.647 --> 00:46:19.516
finding life on other planets.
And the big problem with this

00:46:19.516 --> 00:46:23.852
whole mission is that it's been
cancelled, because a decision

00:46:23.852 --> 00:46:27.250
has been made that it's--this is
a very big,

00:46:27.250 --> 00:46:29.083
expensive mission,
and the decision has been made

00:46:29.083 --> 00:46:31.260
that if you're going to do
something big and expensive,

00:46:31.260 --> 00:46:32.750
you ought to go to Mars,
instead.

00:46:32.750 --> 00:46:36.237
Put people on Mars, instead.
However, this is a twenty-five

00:46:36.237 --> 00:46:38.733
year time scale.
Things get cancelled and

00:46:38.733 --> 00:46:42.442
un-cancelled every three or four
years, so, who knows exactly

00:46:42.442 --> 00:46:46.207
what's going to happen.
And I think this may reappear

00:46:46.207 --> 00:46:49.630
in the NASA plan at some point
in the future.

00:46:49.630 --> 00:46:54.444
And that's sort of the ultimate
that people can think of now in

00:46:54.444 --> 00:46:58.559
terms of find--studying planets
around other stars.

00:46:58.559 --> 00:47:02.725
Okay, that's what I got to say
about this, and a test on

